==1945–49== *1948 [[Netiva Ben-Yehuda]] fights in the [[1948 Arab–Israeli War]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ithl.org.il/author_info.asp?id=50 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-08-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410172559/http://www.ithl.org.il/author_info.asp?id=50 |archivedate=2012-04-10 |df= }}</ref>
==1950s== * 1950: Hate Woman of the [[Kainai Nation]] died. When she married her husband Weasel Tail, she loved him so much that she refused to let him go into battle without her, so that they would never die apart. She went on five raids armed with a six-shooter. On one raid, she stole a saddle, an ammunition bag, and a war club. After another raid, she, her husband and one other man returned with fourteen good horses. Hate Woman was asked to tell her adventures at the [[Sun Dance]] celebration, an unusual honor.<ref>*Hungry Wolf, Beverly, ''The Ways of My Grandmothers'', pp.&nbsp;[https://books.google.com/books?id=oiVyUVvQsYgC&lpg=PP1&dq=%22Hate%20Woman%22%20kainai&pg=PA59#v=onepage&q&f=false 59–60], 112</ref> * 1950: [[Blanca Canales]] leads the [[Jayuya Uprising]] in [[Puerto Rico]] against the [[federal government of the United States]]. After leading rebel forces, she was arrested for the murder of a police officer and the wounding of three others.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1950: [[Korean War]]. Women's Army Corp is created in Korea.<ref>{{cite news|title=Women in the Military: a Bastion of Equal Opportunities|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2008/10/01/2008100161013.html|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]] |date=2009-09-05 |accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref> * 1951: The People's Republic of China begins recruiting female military pilots.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1951: [[Yael Rom]] ({{lang-he|יעל רום}}; 1932–2006), born Yael Finkelstein, was one of the first female pilots of the [[Israeli Air Force]] and the first trained and certified by the force. Rom received her wings on December 27, 1951, graduating the IAF's 5th flying course.<ref name="edge">{{cite book|last=Norton|first=Bill|title=Air War on the Edge - A History of the Israel Air Force and its Aircraft since 1947|publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing|Midland Publishing]]|year=2004|page=105|isbn=1-85780-088-5}}</ref> * 1953: [[Korean war]] ends. Women start serving in the [[South Korea]]n military.<ref>{{Cite news|title=S. Korea gets its 1st female fighter pilots|author=Kyodo News International, Inc., Gale Group|date= September 30, 2002|url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0WDQ/is_2002_Sept_30/ai_93437896|accessdate=2008-06-25}} {{dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref> * 1955: Private Esther Arditi becomes the first female soldier to be awarded an [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] decoration, the [[Medal of Distinguished Service]].{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1953–1959: Cuban women fight in the [[Cuban Revolution]] led by [[Celia Sanchez]] Mandulay, among them [[Haydée Santamaria]].{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 27 September 1955: Chinese [[Li Zhen (female general)|Li Zhen]] is given the [[Order of Liberation (China)|1st Class Order of Liberation]] granted the rank of [[Ranks of the People's Liberation Army Ground Force|Major General]].<ref name=tongyangxi>{{cite web|last1=Wu 吴|first1=Zhife 志菲|title=Li Zhen: cong tongyangxi dao kaiguo jiangjun 李贞：从童养媳到开国将军|url=http://www.people.com.cn/GB/paper81/8389/789549.html|publisher=Renmin Wang|date=2003|accessdate=27 November 2011}}</ref> * 1956: [[Rawya Ateya]] became the first woman to be commissioned as an [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] in the Liberation Army. She played an active role in the [[Suez War]], during which Egypt was invaded by the [[United Kingdom]], [[France]] and [[Israel]]. She helped train 4,000 women in [[first aid]] and [[nursing]] amid the war.<ref name="Goldschmidt">[[#Gol00|Goldschmidt 2000]], p. 26</ref><ref name="Karam">[[#Kar98|Karam 1998]], p. 44</ref> She held the rank of [[Captain (land)|captain]] in a women's [[commando]] unit.<ref name="Sullivan">[[#Sul86|Sullivan 1986]]</ref> * 1956–1957: [[Battle of Algiers (1956–57)]] takes place. Several women participate, including [[Hassiba Ben Bouali]],<ref>Historical Dictionary of Algeria By Phillip C. Naylor, p.71</ref> and [[Zohra Drif]].<ref>Assia Djebar: Out of Algeria By Jane Hiddleston p.36</ref> * 1958–1960: Tibetan Buddhist nun [[Ani Pachen]] leads her clan in armed rebellion against the Chinese.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1958{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}: [[Dương Thu Hương]] leads a communist youth brigade for ten years in the [[Vietnam War]]. She later became a political dissident and is now living in exile from Vietnam.<ref>Encyclopedia of Censorship By Jonathon Green, Nicholas J. Karolides p.157</ref>
==1960s== * 1960: [[Margaret George Shello]] is commonly believed to have been the first female [[Peshmerga]]; she joined the Peshmerga in 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/260620183 |title=Grave of first female Peshmerga renovated |publisher=Rudaw.net |date=2015-06-16 |accessdate=2018-06-27}}</ref> * 1961: Josephine Okwuekeleke Tolefe was the first female Commissioned Officer in the [[Nigerian Army]]; she was granted Short Service Commission on 7 February 1961 in the rank of Second Lieutenant with seniority in the rank with effect from same date.<ref name="vanguardngr.com">{{cite web|last=Ogwuda |first=Austin |url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/2011/12/meet-the-first-female-army-officer-in-nigeria/ |title=Meet the first female army officer in Nigeria |publisher=Just Human |date=December 10, 2011 |accessdate=December 18, 2011}}</ref> * 1961–1964: [[Le Ly Hayslip|Phung Le Ly]] fights for the [[Viet Cong]] during the [[Vietnam War]], an experience she chronicles in her memoir ''[[When Heaven and Earth Changed Places]]''.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1963: Josephine Okwuekeleke Tolefe became the first woman to attain the rank of an Army Captain in Nigeria, which she attained on 1 June 1963.<ref name="vanguardngr.com"/> * 1967: [[Dilma Rousseff]] fights as a [[guerrilla]] in [[Brazil]]. She later became Brazil's first female president.<ref name="YahooNewsGuerrilla">{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20101031/ap_on_re_la_am_ca/lt_brazil_elections |title=Ex-Guerrilla to be Brazil's First Female President |accessdate=2014-08-19 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104010543/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20101031/ap_on_re_la_am_ca/lt_brazil_elections |archivedate=November 4, 2010 |df= }} by Bradley Brooks, ''[[Associated Press]]'', 31 October 2010. Retrieved from Internet Archive 11 January 2014.</ref> * August 31, 1967: [[Haydée Tamara Bunke Bider]], alias Tania the Guerrilla, communist revolutionary, is killed battling Bolivian soldiers.{{fact|date=October 2014}}
==1970s== * 1970s: [[Aminta Granera]] abandons her training as a nun in order to join the [[Sandinistas]] and fight against [[Nicaraguan]] dictator [[Anastasio Somoza Debayle]].{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1970s: [[Fay Chung]] joins [[ZANU]].<ref>Re-living the Second Chimurenga: Memories from Zimbabwe's Liberation Struggle By Fay Chung</ref> * June 22, 1970: [[Dang Thuy Tram]], a Vietnamese military doctor, is killed by United States forces while defending a hospital. Her wartime diaries are published in 2005.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1971: [[Taramon Bibi]] fights Pakistan during the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]].{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1972: Katherine Ravithis became the first woman to join the Colorado Army National Guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greeleytribune.com/news/local/katherine-ravithis-first-woman-to-join-colorado-national-guard-to-be-honored-by-weld-county-veterans-memorial-committee/|title=First woman to join Colorado National Guard to be honored|publisher=}}</ref> * 1973: [[Roza Papo]], Yugoslav military physician, becomes the first female general on the [[Balkan Peninsula]] * 1974: [[Nelida Cabigayan]], a member of the Philippine's New People's Army which was fighting the dictatorship of [[Ferdinand Marcos]], surrenders. She is considered to be a folk hero in the Philippines.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * February 17, 1974: Zimbabwean politician [[Joyce Mujuru]] shoots down a helicopter with a machine gun during the [[Rhodesian Bush War]]. She eventually takes the nom-du-guerre ''Teurai Ropa'' ("Spill Blood"), and then rose to become one of the first women commanders in Mugabe's ZANLA forces.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1974: Maj. Wendy Clay, a doctor, qualifies for her pilot's wings in the Canadian military six years before the pilot classification is opened to all women.<ref name="www2">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/cdnmilitary/women-cdnmilitary.html |title=Women in the Canadian military |publisher=CBC News |date=May 30, 2006 |accessdate=December 18, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128222100/http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/cdnmilitary/women-cdnmilitary.html |archivedate=November 28, 2011 }}</ref> * 1975: [[Nicaraguan]] [[Gioconda Belli]] is forced into exile for her activities as a [[Sandinista]].{{fact|date=October 2014}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.envio.org.ni/articulo/3136|title=Revista Envío - Women, Poetry, New Nicaraguan Culture|website=www.envio.org.ni}}</ref> * 1978: Cpl. Gail Toupin becomes the first female member of the SkyHawks, the Canadian Army's skydiving demonstration team.<ref name="www2"/> * 1979: [[Nora Astorga]] acts as a [[guerrilla]] fighter in the [[Nicaraguan Revolution]].{{fact|date=October 2014}}
==1980s== * 1980: [[Farabundo Martí National Liberation Front]] forms. [[Ana María]] becomes second in command.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1981: 2nd Lieut. Inge Plug becomes the first female helicopter pilot in the Canadian military.<ref name="www2"/> * 1981: Lieut. Karen McCrimmon becomes the Canadian Forces' first female air navigator.<ref name="www2"/> * 1985: Women have been allowed into almost all operational functions of Norway's Armed Forces since 1985. The exceptions are the para-rangers and marine commandos, because as of 2011 no woman has met the entry requirements.<ref name="www1">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/military-international/ |title=Women in the military — international |publisher=CBC News Online |date=May 30, 2006 |accessdate=December 18, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111014025906/http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/military-international/ |archivedate=October 14, 2011 }}</ref> * 1986: Rebecca Mpagi joined the [[National Resistance Army]]; she was the first Ugandan woman to join the army as a military pilot.<ref>{{cite web|last=Okwera |first=Oyet |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201206140623.html |title=Uganda: First Woman Military Pilot (Page 1 of 3) |publisher=allAfrica.com |date=2012-06-13 |accessdate=2013-01-24}}</ref> * 1986–1987: [[Alice Auma]] leads a rebellion against [[Ugandan]] government forces.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1987: All trades are opened to women in the Canadian Forces, including the combat arms. However, women are still restricted from serving in submarines until 2002 when the [[Upholder/Victoria-class submarine|''Victoria''-class submarines]] are acquired.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1988: Col. [[Sheila A. Hellstrom]] is the first female graduate of National Defence College in Canada. She becomes the first Canadian Regular Force woman to be promoted to the rank of brigadier-general.<ref name="www2"/> * 1988: First female gunners in the Canadian Regular Force graduate from qualification 3 training.<ref name="www2"/> * January 19, 1989: [[Canadian Forces]] soldier [[Heather Erxleben]] becomes the first female to graduate from a Regular Force infantry trades training course.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1989: Maj. Dee Brasseur became the first Canadian female fighter pilot of a CF-18 Hornet.<ref name="www2"/> * Late 1980s: Latifa and Lailuma Nabizada become the first female graduates of the [[Afghan Airforce Academy]]. Lailuma eventually died in childbirth, making Latifa the first female pilot in Afghan history.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shafi |first=Ahmad |url=https://www.npr.org/2011/09/15/140147424/for-afghan-female-pilot-a-long-turbulent-journey |title=A Long, Turbulent Journey For Afghan Female Pilot |publisher=NPR |date=September 15, 2011 |accessdate=December 18, 2011}}</ref>
==1990s== * [[Early 1990s]]: [[Jo Salter]] becomes the [[Royal Air Force]]'s first female fighter pilot.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Smyth, Chris|title=Women on the front line|publisher=Times Online|date=June 18, 2008|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article4164468.ece|accessdate=2008-06-25 | location=London}}</ref> * 1991: [[HMCS Nipigon (DDH 266)|HMCS Nipigon]] becomes the first Canadian mixed-gender warship to participate in exercises with NATO's Standing Naval Forces Atlantic.<ref name="www2"/> * 1991: Lieut. Anne Reiffenstein (née Proctor), Lieut. Holly Brown and Capt. Linda Shrum graduate from artillery training as the first female officers in the combat arms in Canada.<ref name="www2"/> * 1992: The [[Presidential Commission on the Assignment of Women in the Armed Forces]] recommends gender-neutral requirements for recruitment to non-combat roles in the United States Armed Forces. * 1992: On July 13, 1992, 22 women began their naval training at INS Mandovi in Goa to become the first commissioned officers in the Indian defence forces. Prior to 1992, the Indian Navy enlisted women only in the role of doctor.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/goa/20-yrs-on-first-women-naval-officers-meet-in-Goa/articleshow/14919824.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=20 yrs on, first women naval officers meet in Goa | date=July 15, 2012}}</ref> * 1993: Lieut. (N) Leanne Crowe is the first woman in Canada to qualify as a clearance diving officer and is subsequently the first woman to become Officer Commanding of the Experimental Diving Unit.<ref name="www2"/> * January 1, 1994: [[Comandante Ramona]], an officer of [[Zapatista Army of National Liberation]], takes control of [[San Cristóbal de las Casas]], a Mexican city.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1994: Maj.-Gen. Wendy Clay becomes the first woman in Canada promoted to that rank.<ref name="www2"/> * 1995: Chief Warrant Officer Linda Smith is the first woman to be named Wing Chief Warrant Officer in the Canadian Forces at 17 Wing Winnipeg.<ref name="www2"/> * 1995: Chief Petty Officer, 2nd Class Holly Kisbee becomes the first woman Combat Chief of a major warship in Canada.<ref name="www2"/> * 1995: Maj. Micky Colton becomes the first female pilot in Canada to complete 10,000 flying hours in a Hercules aircraft.<ref name="www2"/> * 1995: A Norwegian woman, [[Solveig Krey]], became the first female commanding officer of a [[submarine]] in the world when she took command of the first [[Kobben class submarine]] on 11 September 1995.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ftp.rta.nato.int/public/PubFullText/RTO/MP/RTO-MP-HFM-158/MP-HFM-158-05.doc |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-02-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226043717/http://ftp.rta.nato.int/public//PubFullText/RTO/MP/RTO-MP-HFM-158///MP-HFM-158-05.doc |archivedate=2013-02-26 |df= }}</ref> * 1995: Lieut. Ruth-Ann Shamuhn of 5 Combat Engineer Regiment becomes the first female combat diver in Canada.<ref name="www2"/> * 1995: The Royal Norwegian Navy became the first navy in the world to appoint a female submarine captain.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1998: The Australian Navy became the second nation to allow women to serve on combat submarines. Canada and Spain followed in permitting women to serve on military submarines.{{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1998: Brigadier Patricia Purves becomes the first British one-star general selected in open competition across the [[British Army]]. (The [[Women's Royal Army Corps]], disbanded in 1992, had a 'tied' brigadier appointment.){{fact|date=October 2014}} * 1998: Although women had served as pilots during the [[1948 Arab-Israeli War|Israeli War of Independence]] and a few years thereafter, the [[Israeli Defense Forces]] had until 1995 denied women the opportunity to become pilots. After the prohibition was lifted, the first female graduate was [[F-16]] navigator "Shari" in 1998.<ref name="edge"/> * January 1999: [[Indonesia]]n woman Cut Syamsurniati successfully leads a group of women to negotiate with the military when her village is attacked.<ref>{{cite news| first=Andrew |last=Marshall |title=Cut Syamsurniati: In Aceh, a woman warrior fights against fear|url=http://www.time.com/time/asia/2003/heroes/cut_syamsurniati.html|work=[[TIME Magazine]] |date=2003-04-28 |accessdate=2008-01-28|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100527232025/http://www.time.com/time/asia/2003/heroes/cut_syamsurniati.html |archivedate = May 27, 2010|deadurl=yes}}</ref> * 1999: Arlene dela Cruz became the first woman to graduate at the top of her class at the Philippine Military Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/139071/news/regions/pma-s-1st-woman-topnotcher-laid-to-rest |title=PMA’s 1st woman topnotcher laid to rest &#124; News &#124; GMA News Online &#124; The Go-To Site for Filipinos Everywhere |publisher=Gmanetwork.com |date=2008-12-12 |accessdate=2013-01-24}}</ref>
